The Paris stock exchange was slightly up Monday in  thin trading while London and New York were closed as a result of bank  holidays in Britain and the United States.
After finishing the week at its lowest level this year, the CAC 40 index  ended the day up 0.09 percent at 2,052.51 points.
On Friday, the CAC 40 lost some 2.5 percent during the course of the day,  recovering slightly to close just above 2,050 points.
At Monday's close, shares in the Schneider company, whose boss was jailed  Friday in Belgium in connection with an enquiry into alleged wrongdoings  within Belgium subsidiaries, had regained 2.54 percent after a drop of 5.6  percent on Friday.
Eurotunnel was up 5.12 percent, Synthelabo up 4.34 percent and the Colbert  Bank up 4.17 percent.
CCMC Managix was down 5.35 percent and Dassault Aviation down by 3.47  percent.
Meanwhile in Frankfurt, the DAX lost 22.84 points at 2,118.15, while the  Commerzbank index was down 35.80 points at 2,288.40.
Mannesmann, despite predictions of a return to profit this year, lost 14  marks, while Deutsche Babcock was down by 6.90 marks and FAG-Kugfelfisher down  by 8 marks.
Daimler was also down by 15.5 marks, BMW by 13 marks, Preussag by 10.5  marks, Deutsche Bank and VW by 7 marks and Hoechst by 5.50 marks.
In Madrid, trading was very thin and the index was down 0.09 points to  330.81 points.
In Amsterdam, the stock exchange ended the day with the EOE index gaining  0.79 points at 402.42 points.
